post_text:
To our SLCS families,

We have been thrilled and honored to provide food to your family during this time of uncertainty. We hope that the food that we delivered was enjoyed and helped to provide nourishment and a bit of comfort.

We wanted to share with you some resources to help with food over the summer:

SCHROON LAKE FOOD PANTRY
11 BROAD ST.
SCHROON LAKE, NY 12870

Community outreach

Also, the USDA National Hunger Hotline remains a helpful resource for people seeking food assistance. The hotline, operated by Hunger Free America, can be reached Monday through Friday between 7 a.m. to 10 p.m. ET. at 1-866-3-HUNGRY (1-866-348-6479) or 1-877-8-HAMBRE (1-877-842-6273) (for Spanish).

Families can be provided with the following information to quickly and easily find summer meals near them.

Text: “food” to 877-877
Call: 1-866-3-HUNGRY or 211
https://www.fns.usda.gov/meals4kids
www.summermealsny.org

Best Wishes,
Julie Holbrook – Cafeteria Manager

Schroon Lake School Budget Passes

SLCS would like to thank the voters and the tax payers for supporting the school. We would also like to thank all those who helped make it possible for us to create a budget that represents a $141,000 decrease in spending from the previous year.

We wish to congratulate Jarod Whitley and Ashley Berry who won the election for the school board. Mr. Whitleywill begin serving his 3 year term on July 1st. Ms. Berry will begin serving her 1 year term on July 1st.

Thank you for your continued support of our students!

post_text:
Governor Changes Deadline for Mail-in Budget Votes

In an executive order issued over the weekend, the NYS Governor extended mail-in absentee budget votes until June 16th. As previously planned, all absentee ballot votes that are being dropped off at school must be dropped off by June 9th at 5 pm. However, we will still accept mail-in budget votes until we collect the mail from the post office on June 16th.

As a result of the change, Schroon Lake Central School will not be counting any of the votes that have been cast or will be cast until 5:00 pm on June 16th.

On June 16th at 5 pm , we will livestream the counting of the budget vote. After the votes are counted on June 16th, we will hold a board meeting to consider/accept the results of the vote.

School Budget Vote

Dear Tax Payers,

We wanted to let you know that we have received some budget vote return envelopes that have not been filled out correctly. Please be very careful when filling out the envelope. You must fill out all information including your name, residence, city, town, and school district You must also fill include your signature and the date. If you do not fill out all of this information we will be unable to verify the ballot was filled out by a qualified district voter and we will not be able to count your vote.

If you feel that you may have returned an envelope to the district that was not properly filled out, please call Lisa DeZalia at 518-532-7164.

Thank you,

Stephen Gratto - Superintendent

post_text:
Schroon Lake Central School gets an $8000 grant from the Adirondack Foundation

Our school has been blessed with an $8000 grant from the Adirondack Foundation to help us with procuring local food to feed families during the COVID-19 crisis!

We are so thankful and look forward to sending every family that is receiving meals food from the following amazing local farms and farm hubs – Juniper Hill Farm in Wadhams, North Country Creamery in Keeseville, Essex Farm in Essex, Donahue’s Livestock Farm in Malone, and the Hub on the Hill in Essex.

The Adirondack Foundation is a regular supporter of SLCS. Recently, they donated $5000 to the school to purchase cleaning supplies and personal care items for the people in the Schroon Lake community. Earlier this year they donated money to help buy a 3D printer for the tech department. In the past, they have given us money to purchase most of the video and TV equipment that we use in our videography class and club.

Thank you Adirondack Foundation!

https://www.adirondackfoundation.org/granting/special-and-urgent-needs-fund-sun

The Freshman Class Bottle Box is Open for Business

Actually, it is really more of a sign now. If you wish to donate your returnable bottles and cans to the Freshman class to help them pay for things like the junior prom and the senior trip, we would greatly appreciate it.

Please just leave your bags or boxes of returnable bottles or cans behind the sign which is across from the school and next to the Catholic Church.

We will take the bags and bottles and store them away for fourteen days before sorting them. Students will not touch the bottles or boxes for fourteen days after you drop them off.

Thank you in advance for your donation.

post_text:
Schroon Lake....The Cleanest Town in the Adirondacks

Today we delivered bags of cleaning supplies and personal care items to 125 families in Schroon Lake. We have several extra bags of supplies that we are happy to donate to any family or community member who might need one. Please e-mail sgratto@slwildcats.org if you would like us to drop a bag off to you or if you are a family that would like a second bag.

Thanks go to the Adirondack Foundation for donating $5000 to make the purchase of these items possible. Thank you to Dollar General for procuring and packaging all of these items. Thank you to the Peace Family who helped package and deliver the bags to the school. Thanks to Board Member Sue Repko for writing the grant application. Thanks to the custodians, aides, and cafeteria workers who delivered the bags to the houses.

Stay clean everybody!

In response to the COVID-19 public health emergency, the New York State of Health has made a Special Enrollment Period available to New Yorkers during which eligible individuals will be able to enroll in insurance coverage through NY State of Health, New York’s official health plan Marketplace, and directly through insurers. The Special Enrollment Period is open from March 16 to May 15, 2020. Medicaid, Essential Plan and Child Health Plus – can enroll year-round.

The Fidelis Care team is ready to assist you by phone. Call 1-866-435-9521 (TTY: 711) or you can contact your local Fidelis Care Representative, Katelyn Smart 518-593-5341 or Matthew Davis 518-429-8224.

Thank You International Paper and the Adirondack Foundation

The SLCS Technology Department has received a $1500 grant from the International Paper Company and a $590 grant from the Adirondack Foundation.

These funds will be used to support the purchase of a MakerBot Method 3D printer to be used in the SLCS Technology classes.

SLCS is very thankful for the generous support provided by International Paper and the Adirondack Foundation. Our students will benefit greatly by having this new technology in our school.

Additional thanks go to School Board Member Sue Repko for writing and submitting the associated grant applications.

There will be a school board meeting today at 12:30 pm.

We will livestream the board meeting on our school facebook page and public participation will be possible by typing in comments or calling the school at 518-569-0931.

It is anticipated that the board will immediately go into executive session to discuss the medical, financial, credit or employment history of a particular person or corporation, or matters leading to the appointment, employment, promotion, demotion, discipline, suspension, dismissal or removal of a particular person or corporation;

There will be no action taken when the board goes back into session. The meeting will end soon after the executive session.

post_text:
Memo Regarding: Childcare for Essential Workers and First Responders

Dear Schroon Lake Residents,

Governor Cuomo has mandated that schools establish a plan for providing information about accessing daycare for essential workers and first responders.

While we are not aware of any licensed daycare providers in Schroon Lake, we are working with the Adirondack Community Action Program in Elizabethtown to address the issue.

For a complete list of Governor Cuomo’s Guidance on Essential workers under the “New York State on Pause” Executive order, you can follow this link:

https://www.governor.ny.gov/news/governor-cuomo-issues-guidance-essential-services-under-new-york-state-pause-executive-order

If you are an essential worker or if you are a first responder, and if you are in need of child care, we encourage you to call us at Schroon Lake Central School or to call Kellie LaClair, the Program Coordinator at ACAP. Kelly can be reached at kleclair@acapinc.org (518)873-3207 x246.

Sincerely,

Stephen Gratto - Superintendent

post_text:
Schroon Lake hosted an archery tournament at the beginning of March. Thank you Coach Sharp and Coach Wisser for making it happen.

Seven schools and 84 archers participated . Several schools were first time competitive archery teams. Schools in attendance were Schroon Lake, Johnsburg, Newcomb, Hoosick Falls, Eldred, Norwich, and Boquet Valley.

Many of our Schroon Lake Archers metaled and many shot in their first ever competition. Well done archers.

Huge congrats to Dawson Dezalia on his personal best on bullseye shoot with 293 out of 300. This sets a new SLCS bullseye competition record.

3-8 Math, Science, and ELA Tests will not occur this year

Dear Faculty, Staff, and Parents,

Here is some news, hot off of the presses. The 3-8 state tests including ELA, Math, and Science will not occur this year. These tests were originally planned for April and May.

It is important to remember that, at this time, regents exams are scheduled to go on as planned.

Please let me know if you have any questions. You can read the actual announcement by the State Ed Department by checking out this webpage:

Stephen Gratto

http://www.nysed.gov/news/2020/statement-board-regents-chancellor-betty-rosa-and-interim-state-education-commissioner-2

3-8 Math, Science, and ELA Tests will not occur this year

Dear Faculty, Staff, and Parents,

Here is some news, hot off of the presses. The 3-8 state tests including ELA, Math, and Science will not occur this year. These tests were originally planned for April and May.

It is important to remember that, at this time, regents exams are scheduled to go on as planned.

Please let me know if you have any questions. You can read the actual announcement by the State Ed Department by checking out this webpage:

Stephen Gratto

http://www.nysed.gov/news/2020/statement-board-regents-chancellor-betty-rosa-and-interim-state-education-commissioner-2

NYSED.GOV
Statement From Board of Regents Chancellor Betty A. Rosa and Interim State Education Commissioner Shannon Tahoe Regarding Elementary- and Intermediate-Level State Assessments

4th Grade Snow Shoe Trip

4th graders returned to the Adirondack Mountain Club for the second trip of the 3 Seasons at Heart Lake Program. They ended their day writing and performing Haiku poetry about their experiences in nature.

New Visions Medical Program at CVTEC

Dr. Todd Menia of the New Visions Program at the CVES BOCES came to SLCS to discuss the program with juniors and seniors. Students attend school in Elizabethtown half of every school day and they spend a great deal of time working onsite at the Elizabethtown Hospital.

Ruth Jabaut Earns President's List Honors at SUNY Canton
Jan 7

SUNY Canton President Zvi Szafran congratulates Ruth Jabaut for earning academic honors during the Fall 2019 Semester.

"In recognition of your success, I'm pleased to include your name on the SUNY Canton President's List," Szafran said. "This honor is awarded to full-time students who achieve a 3.75 or greater grade point average. You have demonstrated a great commitment to your academic studies and should be proud of your accomplishments."

Community Trivia Night is Back!

This is a low pressure game that is fun for all. If you are looking for a fun family evening or a chance for you and your co-workers or friends to have a fun night out, come to trivia night. Assemble your team of up to four adults (students in grades K-5 can come and participate but they don't count toward the total of 4). Answer questions, eat refreshments, and hang out with your friends.

The Freshman class appreciates your support.
